I loved this recent piece very much. And I feel that The Awl was at least as much a reader's website as it was a writer's one.

I’m still writing to satisfy my private interest  not as a career. But I wanted to add my voice to the chorus of mourners and to footnote how much @Awl has meant to me as a reader and a still-mostly-private writer.
I've really enjoyed following writers I admire from The Awl as they publish or get jobs elsewhere. It's been fun today to read the impact The Awl had on their careers.
The Awl also led me to @CAAF  whose Book Beast program has helped me so much to grow so much as a writer (and person.)
And for some reason they paid me real money to write about my Dad’s rock concert obsession! Which was something I’d wanted to do for years and cannot imagine finding encouragement for elsewhere.
It was a thrill when @silviakillings said yes to my pitch last year about a forgotten Nazi memoir and an education to see what her editing did to my writing.

But it was important to me as a writer as well  a kind of true north for the kind of things I hoped to write and see published: particular  sharp  and divorced from the news cycle. Something written to satisfy a private interest but for a smart public audience.
I’m grieving @Awl mostly as a reader. It was someplace to go to read something good about a topic I didn’t even know I could be interested in. It made me more curious as well as less stupid.
